README for zaproxy-bin


LOOK AND FEEL

  Add the following lines into ~/.bash_profile:

    xprop -root -f _NET_WM_NAME 32a -set _NET_WM_NAME LG3D

    export DESKTOP_SESSION=gnome
    export AWT_TOOLKIT=MToolkit
    export _JAVA_AWT_WM_NONREPARENTING=1

  And, in case if you have terminus-like fonts system-wide,
  add this line (disabled antialiasing mode):

    export _JAVA_OPTIONS="\
    -Dawt.useSystemAAFontSettings=off \
    -Dswing.aatext=false \
    -Dswing.defaultlaf=com.sun.java.swing.plaf.gtk.GTKLookAndFeel \
    -Dswing.crossplatformlaf=com.sun.java.swing.plaf.gtk.GTKLookAndFeel"

  Otherwise, add this (enabled antialiasing mode):

    export _JAVA_OPTIONS="\
    -Dawt.useSystemAAFontSettings=on \
    -Dswing.aatext=true \
    -Dswing.defaultlaf=com.sun.java.swing.plaf.gtk.GTKLookAndFeel \
    -Dswing.crossplatformlaf=com.sun.java.swing.plaf.gtk.GTKLookAndFeel"


DIFFERENT USER

  Add the user:
    # useradd -U -m zaproxy

  Change the user's appearance:
    $ xhost +SI:localuser:zaproxy
    $ sudo -u zaproxy -H lxappearance

  Use this wrapper as zaproxy launcher:
    #!/bin/sh
    xhost +SI:localuser:zaproxy
    sudo -u zaproxy -H /usr/bin/zaproxy-weekly
    # End of file.

  Sudo without a password:
    # cat > /etc/sudoers.d/zaproxy <<EOF
    user ALL=(zaproxy) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/zaproxy-weekly
    EOF

    # usermod -aG audio,video zaproxy

  Add settings from <LOOK AND FEEL> section to .bash_profile:
    $ sudo -u zaproxy vim ~/.bash_profile

  Also, if you run firefox as different user and have 
  the launcher in /opt/bin, add correct PATH to .bash_profile:
    export PATH="/bin:/sbin:/usr/bin:/usr/sbin:/opt/bin:/opt/sbin"

End of file.
